{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778553730,"nonce":"NhhOLqvTmS4PV2/os2z30amCqRo=","message":"**Analytical tracker = analytical regulator (2026-05-11)**\n\nFor a linear system, the optimal tracker and optimal regulator produce the exact same control law algebraically. When u_ff = -K·x_nom, the tracker decomposition collapses: u_ff - K·(x - x_nom) = -K·x_nom - K·x + K·x_nom = -K·x. Same gains, same Δv.\n\nThis means the d448c9d question **cannot be answered by extending the existing Riccati solver** with a tracker form — the analytical extension would just confirm this algebraic identity. The question is specifically about whether *learned* controllers with independently parameterized u_ff(t) and K_t (not jointly optimal) produce different Δv due to the parameterization giving the optimizer freedom to decouple feedforward drive from feedback stiffness. That's a question about learning dynamics, not optimal control theory — you need to actually train the architectures.\n\nImplication: Stage 0 (03a148a, LQG vs H∞ analytical comparison) is still valuable as a ground-truth baseline, but the decoupling test requires training, not analytics.","files":null}]}